 aspects of everyday life that remained the same, or similar, notwithstanding the efforts of the kirk, employers and the state to alter behaviours and attitudes.Drawing upon and interrogating a range of primary sources, the authors create a richly coloured, highly-nuanced picture of the lives of ordinary Scots from birth through marriage to death. Analytical in approach, the coverage of topics is wide, ranging from the ways people made a living, through their non-work activities including reading, playing and relationships, to the ways they experienced illness and approached death.This volume:Provides a rich and finely nuanced social history of the period 1600-1800Gets behind the politics of Union and Jacobitism, and the experience of agricultural and industrial 'revolution'Presents the scholarly expertise of its contributing authors in a accessible wayIncludes a guide to further reading indicating sources for further study"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 4aScottish Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh1 aDingwall, Helen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDodgshon, Robert A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurie, Alastair, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoyster, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Bob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKean, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Joyce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNenadic, Stana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSymonds, Deborah A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhatley, Christopher A., econtributor.4ctb